{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:50:36.804018", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network state assessment\n\nSummary\n- Network control plane: OSPF is converged across cores and server-access router; routes for user subnets (10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24) and the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) are present and exchanged.\n- Data-plane: Hosts and servers are reachable end-to-end with low latency and no packet loss.\n- Primary abnormality: Backend web servers (10.200.0.3–.6) are directly reachable from user hosts. That contradicts the stated design requirement that backend web servers must not be directly accessible from hosts (hosts should reach services via the load balancer only).\n- Localization: Evidence points to server_access_router (or the lack of access control applied there/in the routing/ACL plane) as the place where traffic segmentation is not enforced.\n- Root-cause hypothesis: Access control segmentation intended to block host → backend-web direct traffic is missing or misconfigured (ACLs/firewall rules not applied on the server-facing router or along the forwarding path), allowing routed connectivity to the backend subnet.\n\nWhat I checked (tools & outputs used)\n1) Reachability sweep (summary mapping)\n- Hosts and server IPs observed:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 = 10.1.1.10\n  - host_2_1_1_1 = 10.2.1.10\n  - dhcp_server = 10.200.0.8\n  - dns_server = 10.200.0.2\n  - web_server_0..3 = 10.200.0.3–.6\n  - load_balancer = 10.200.0.7\n- No packet loss observed between internal nodes in the sweep.\n\n2) OSPF / routing (FRR outputs)\n- server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected on br0:\n  - \"10.200.0.0/24 [110/10] is directly connected, br0\"\n  - This means server farm subnet is routable and advertised via OSPF (routes exist on other routers).\n- Core routers have OSPF-learned routes to 10.200.0.0/24 (via next-hops on inter-core links), e.g.:\n  - router_core_1: \"O>* 10.200.0.0/24 [110/30] via 172.16.0.3, eth1\"\n  - router_core_2: \"O>* 10.200.0.0/24 [110/30] via 172.16.0.5, eth1\"\n  - router_core_3: \"O>* 10.200.0.0/24 [110/20] via 172.16.0.11, eth2\"\n- OSPF summaries show full adjacencies and area attachments consistent with a converged topology.\n\n3) Host → server pings (selected)\n- host_1_1_1_1 → web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 4/4 replies, avg RTT ≈ 3.26 ms\n- host_1_1_1_1 → web_server_1 (10.200.0.4): 4/4 replies, avg RTT ≈ 3.52 ms\n- host_1_1_1_1 → web_server_3 (10.200.0.6): 4/4 replies, avg RTT ≈ 2.90 ms\n- host_1_1_1_1 → load_balancer (10.200.0.7): 4/4 replies, avg RTT ≈ 3.76 ms\n- host_2_1_1_1 → web_server_0/1/3: all 4/4 replies, low ms latency\n- Reachability output also shows host → DNS and host → web_server_2 OK.\n\nFindings and evidence supporting the abnormality\n- Intended design: backend web servers should not be directly reachable by user hosts (only via load balancer).\n- Actual behavior: Hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 can successfully ping 10.200.0.3–.6 (web backends). Example evidence:\n  - Ping results from host_1_1_1_1 to web_server_0..3 all show 0% packet loss and RTTs in low ms range.\n  - OSPF/routing confirms the server subnet 10.200.0.0/24 is advertised across the network and is reachable via server_access_router (10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected on br0).\n- Therefore the network is forwarding host-originated packets into the backend server subnet; nothing in the routing path is preventing that traffic.\n\nLocalization — where the problem likely is\n- The intersection point where segmentation should be enforced is the server-facing router (server_access_router) or upstream device(s) configured to block direct host → backend traffic. Evidence:\n  - server_access_router has 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected and is advertising it via OSPF.\n  - Core routers have OSPF routes to 10.200.0.0/24; traffic flows from hosts to server_access_router and then to the backend servers as shown by successful pings and low latency.\n- Less likely (but possible): ACLs/filters intended to enforce the policy could be misconfigured or absent on core routers or distribution routers; however the most direct place to enforce host-to-backend blocking is the server-access-router (it’s the device directly connected to the server network).\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis\n- Segmentation/filtering intended to prevent direct host access to backend web servers is not present or misapplied:\n  - Either ACLs/firewall rules were never applied, were removed, or are misconfigured on the server_access_router (or the equivalent firewall appliance), so routing + OSPF distribution allows host subnets to reach the backend subnet.\n  - Because OSPF advertises the server subnet and routing is in place, routing alone enables the connectivity; blocking must be implemented at policy/ACL level — and that appears absent or ineffective.\n\nOther observations (network health)\n- OSPF shows full adjacencies and reasonable LSA counts — control plane healthy.\n- DHCP and DNS connectivity: dhcp_server and dns_server are reachable from hosts and servers (no packet loss).\n- Latency is low and consistent across the network for ICMP probes.\n\nRecommended next diagnostic checks (for verification; not remediation)\n- Inspect ACLs/firewall rules on server_access_router (br0/eth7) to confirm whether traffic is being filtered or not (e.g., show access-lists / iptables / nftables).\n- Check whether server farm bridge br0 is incorrectly bridging or exposing services beyond intended boundaries.\n- Check load_balancer configuration to verify that it is configured for proxying/load-balancing only and not performing any unintended routing/NAT that would expose the backends.\n- If a separate firewall appliance exists, collect its policy/ACL and logs for host -> backend traffic.\n\nConclusion\n- Network is operational and routes are converged; hosts can reach servers (DNS, DHCP, load balancer and backend web servers).\n- The significant anomaly is policy-level: host-to-backend direct reachability contradicts the design goal that backends must not be directly accessible. The evidence localizes this to missing/incorrect access control on the path — most likely on server_access_router (or an absent firewall policy).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11349, "output_tokens": 3090, "total_tokens": 14439, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 8832}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1472}}}
